Load phyloseq object (full otter dataset)

physeq <- readRDS("/docker_access/sea_otter/vPaper/physeq_dec18.rds")

Retain only wild sea otter gingival samples No duplicate samples per individual sea otter

physeq <- subset_samples(physeq, facility == "CDFW") 
physeq <- subset_samples(physeq, duplicate_capture == "no")
ps_rectal_orig <- subset_samples(physeq, sample_type == "rectal")

Transform the data to be proportions
(this is ok while we are not doing differential abundance analysis)

ps_rectal <- transform_sample_counts(ps_rectal_orig, function(x) x/sum(x))

Cluster into community profiles

Use bray curtis distance metric:
1. Don’t know if closely related strains may be having an effect -> choose a non-phylogenetically informed metric
2. If two sets of samples both have species A, but in one set relative abundance is usually 1% and in the other it’s usually 99%, that information is significant -> choose a metric that uses relative abundance

braydist <- phyloseq::distance(ps_rectal, method="bray")
ord = ordinate(ps_rectal, method = "MDS", distance = braydist)

Retain only the most significant dimensions

Now choose only the most significant eigenvalues to reduce noise in the dataset.
First plot the eigenvalues

plot_scree(ord) + xlim(as.character(seq(1,15))) + ggtitle("MDS-bray ordination eigenvalues")

The first two or so look significant, but after that it’s hard to tell Plot histograms to get a better idea of where to draw the cutoff

evs <- ord$value$Eigenvalues
h_all <- hist(evs, 100)

plot(h_all$mids, h_all$count, log="y", type='h', lwd=10, lend=2)
## Warning in xy.coords(x, y, xlabel, ylabel, log): 73 y values <= 0 omitted
## from logarithmic plot

Choose eigenvalues 1-5 -> 5 MDS dimensions

Determine the number of clusters

NDIM <- 5

Determine the number of clusters using the gap statistic
Use the selection criteria proposed by Tibshirani et al (2001)

x <- ord$vectors[,1:NDIM]  

pamPCoA = function(x, k) {
    list(cluster = pam(x[,1:2], k, cluster.only = TRUE))
}

set.seed(04122018) # today's date
gap_stat = clusGap(x, FUN = pamPCoA, K.max = 10, B = 100)
## Clustering k = 1,2,..., K.max (= 10): .. done
## Bootstrapping, b = 1,2,..., B (= 100)  [one "." per sample]:
## .................................................. 50 
## .................................................. 100
fviz_gap_stat(gap_stat, maxSE = list(method = "Tibs2001SEmax"))

Based on this analysis, it appears there are six clusters

Perform clustering

K <- 6
x <- ord$vectors[,1:NDIM]
clust <- as.factor(pam(x, k=K, cluster.only=T))
sample_data(ps_rectal)$CP <- clust
CPs <- as.character(seq(K))

Save identified CPs in the phyloseq “ps_rectal” and “ps_rectal_orig” objects for later use

sample_data(ps_rectal)$CP <- clust
sample_data(ps_rectal_orig)$CP <- clust

Visualize clustering results with MDA ordination

p = plot_ordination(ps_rectal, ord, color="CP") + 
    scale_color_manual(values=c("#f44242","#b79e30","#397a43", "#00c0c3", "#629ef9", "#fcc1ff"))
plot(p)

There appear to be six distinct clusters

Perform redundancy analysis (RDA)

#Perform ordination by community profile
ps_rectal.ord <- ordinate(ps_rectal, "RDA", "bray", formula=ps_rectal~CP)
evals <- eigenvals(ps_rectal.ord)

#Plot the CP ordination and add biplot with taxa, scale axes by magnitude of variance explained
p = plot_ordination(ps_rectal, ps_rectal.ord, type="biplot", color="CP") +
    coord_fixed(sqrt(evals[2] / evals[1])) 

# Adjust aesthetic parameters of ordination 
p = p +  scale_size_manual(values=c(2,2,2,2)) +
    # grey (taxa)
    scale_color_manual(values=c("#9a9c9e","#f44242","#b79e30","#397a43", "#00c0c3", "#629ef9", "#fcc1ff"))
## Scale for 'size' is already present. Adding another scale for 'size',
## which will replace the existing scale.
plot(p)

ggsave('rda_rectal.pdf', plot = p)
